<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   CBS Profit Rose
   By 16% to Record
   In Second Quarter
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   CBS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- CBS Inc. posted a 16% increase in
second-quarter net income, helped by broadcasting the
National Basketball Association playoff and championship
games and by a drop in programming costs from a year earlier.
   The profit was a second-quarter record, but CBS said the
prospect for continued growth for the balance of the year was
"uncertain" amid a sluggish economy and increased costs for
rights to major sports events.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Profit rose to $138 million, or $5.36 a share, from $118.8
million, or $4.62 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 7% to
$828.8 million from $771.8 million.
   CBS, the No. 3-rated network in prime time for the third
consecutive year, is gambling $3.6 billion over the next few
years on broadcast rights to big sports events, including
four-year major league baseball and football packages that
will begin this year. Each four-year deal is priced at $1.06
billion.
   CBS Broadcast Group, which includes the network, TV and
radio stations and news and sports divisions and is CBS's
only major subsidiary, posted a 31% gain in pretax operating
profit to $180.9 million from $137.9 million.
   Laurence A. Tisch, CBS president and chief executive
officer, said in a statement that the gain was because of
"improved" results at each of the three broadcast divisions,
the television network, television stations and radio. The
earnings at the television network, he said, were "enhanced"
by an expanded number of NBA playoff and championship games
and decreased entertainment programming costs related mainly
to the writers' strike which pushed costs into the second
quarter of 1989."
   The 1989 second quarter was unusual because of the
writers' strike, which resulted in a delay of the 1988-89
prime-time season. As a result, programming costs increased
in that quarter because the networks broadcast more original
programming than usual. Traditionally, the networks begin
airing series repeats in the second quarter.
   CBS's earnings "were much better than I expected," said
Jessica Rief, an analyst at First Boston Corp. Nevertheless,
Ms. Rief said she did not expect third and fourth quarter
results would meet year-earlier levels.
   Commenting on the frenzied one-week period when
advertisers buy commercial time in advance of the 1990-91
prime time season, Ms. Rief said, "CBS took in $100 million
less in up-front advertising this year compared to last year
and, let's face it, they're getting increasing competition
from Fox" Broadcasting Co. Fox, a unit of News Corp., is
increasing the number of nights it programs to five from
three in September.
   Moreover, Ms. Rief noted, the NBA, which helped CBS in the
second quarter, recently signed a deal to be broadcast on
National Broadcasting Co.'s network. NBC is a unit of General
Electric Co.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, CBS
stock closed at $198.50 a share, up 62.5 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900712-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900712-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Anti-Crime Bill
   Wins Passage
   In the Senate
   ---
   Measure Includes Provisions
   Aimed at Invigorating
   Probes of Thrift Fraud
   ----
   By Paul M. Barrett
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate overwhelmingly approved a
wide-ranging anti-crime bill that includes a partial ban on
semiautomatic "assault weapons" and numerous provisions aimed
at invigorating the investigation and prosecution of
savings-and-loan fraud.
   The omnibus bill, which passed 94-6, also would expand the
federal death penalty to cover 34 crimes, curb the
constitutional appeals process for death-row inmates, and
provide $900 million in federal assistance to local
law-enforcement agencies in the coming fiscal year -- twice
the amount proposed by the Bush administration.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Eager to appear tough on the widespread looting of S&amp;Ls,
senators increased penalties for financial fraud, including a
new statute that would provide up to life imprisonment for
high-level thrift executives who conspire with three or more
other violators and derive more than $5 million from their
crimes. Other provisions would provide prosecutors with
broader authorization to use civil seizure and forfeiture
laws in bank and S&amp;L fraud cases.
   The Senate also authorized new spending of $162.5 million
for each of the next three years to hire more federal
investigators and prosecutors devoted strictly to
financial-institution cases. That amount would be in addition
to $50 million appropriated for such cases for the current
fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30. In addition, the Senate
authorized funds to hire 2,500 new federal agents and 480
prosecutors to deal with drug trafficking and other crimes.
   The House is considering omnibus crime legislation of its
own, including various S&amp;L enforcement provisions. But it
isn't clear when the full House will vote on these measures.
Equally unclear is whether President Bush would back a crime
package that includes the Senate's three-year ban on nine
types of assault weapons.
   The Senate's rush to provide new money for thrift-fraud
prosecutions by the Justice Department came as the House
Appropriations Committee voted to give the Treasury
Department's Secret Service expanded authority to initiate
its own investigations of S&amp;L-related crimes. The provision
is attached to a fiscal 1991 bill funding the Treasury
Department and is likely to touch off a turf war with the
Federal Bureau of Investigation, an arm of the Justice
Department that has tried to stop efforts by the Secret
Service to become more involved in reducing the current
backlog of thousands of cases.
   Reflecting an apparent decision by the White House, the
Treasury officially opposes the expanded authority. But
behind the scenes, the Secret Service has promised allies in
Congress that it can make as many as 100 agents available
immediately, and 300 within the next fiscal year.
   The Senate's election-year anti-crime package, which
seemed dead only several weeks ago, jumped back to life with
a high-voltage shock of S&amp;L rhetoric. "We need to be cracking
down on the orgy of fraud and lawbreaking that occurred in
the savings-and-loan crisis," said Sen. Patrick Leahy (D.,
Vt.). The hefty batch of thrift-fraud provisions was added to
the omnibus bill at the last minute, with almost no partisan
bickering.
   Last month, a filibuster orchestrated by the National
Rifle Association had threatened to kill the entire package.
But the powerful NRA repeatedly was unable to muster a
majority to eliminate the prohibition on assault weapons.
Meanwhile, quiet negotiations led by Sens. Joseph Biden (D.,
Del.) and Strom Thurmond (R., S.C.) kept the bill alive until
the almost desperate desire by lawmakers to take action on
the S&amp;L issue assured its passage.
   Many of the S&amp;L-related provisions added to the Senate
bill, such as the provision for life imprisonment for "S&amp;L
kingpins," appeared to be largely symbolic. Others included
those that merely formalize special thrift-fraud task forces
already created by the Justice Department.
   The crime bill also would facilitate speedier restitution
to victims of S&amp;L fraud, allow for public disclosure of
regulatory enforcement actions, and permit the government to
undo fraudulent transactions made by thrift executives.
Another provision would encourage individuals to report S&amp;L
fraud to authorities by providing rewards for information
leading to convictions or civil recoveries. In civil cases,
the amount of such rewards would be tied to the value of
assets recovered and could total hundreds of thousands of
dollars.
   William Seidman, chairman of the Resolution Trust Corp.,
urged Congress to pass the crime bill, saying it would "prove
to be a formidable deterrent to financial institution fraud
and abuse."
   In a hearing before a House Judiciary subcommittee, Mr.
Seidman also defended the government's record in pursuing
crooked S&amp;L directors and officers. The agency recovered more
than $100 million last year in liability claims against S&amp;L
executives, he said, and an additional $200 million in
settlements and judgments in the first half of 1990.
   The Senate dropped from the crime package a provision that
would have allowed, under certain circumstances, the use of
illegally gathered evidence in criminal trials.
   ---
   David Rogers contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900712-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900712-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Semiconductor Industry's
   Leading Indicator Declines
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<IN>
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. -- The semiconductor industry's leading
indicator dropped in June, reflecting seasonal factors and a
surge of orders earlier in the year that skewed June's index.
   The Semiconductor Industry Association's so-called
book-to-bill ratio for June fell to 1.06-to-1 from 1.14-to-1
in May. Both figures are preliminary. A book-to-bill rate of
1.06 means that for every $100 in products shipped, makers
received $106 in new orders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The lower index shows that "we're headed for a normal
reasonable summer, not any kind of recession," said analyst
Erik Jansen of Robertson Stephens &amp; Co. Orders typically fall
in mid-June, he said. And a rash of memory-chip orders in
March translated into deliveries in June that drove the index
down because of lower bookings in the month, he said.
   The industry association late last year forecast a year of
no growth or slightly negative growth and June's index is
"right on target," said an association official.
   June billings were $1.30 billion, 5% lower than the $1.36
billion posted in June 1989. Average monthly bookings for the
three-month period ending in June were $1.27 billion, 1.3%
higher than the year-earlier average bookings of $1.25
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900712-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900712-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   News Corp. Unit's Acquisition
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NWS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SYDNEY, Australia -- Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. said
yesterday that its Harper-Collins Publishers Inc. unit has
agreed to buy British-based book publisher Unwin Hyman Ltd.
   News Corp. didn't reveal the price of the transaction in a
statement to the Australian Stock Exchange, but it said Unwin
Hyman's group annual sales exceeded #15 million ($27.3
million) in 1989, and is split evenly between the U.K. and
overseas.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Unwin Hyman's Australian and New Zealand units aren't
included in the transaction, but the U.S. unit, Unwin Hyman
Inc. of Boston, will become part of Harper-Collins North
America.
   In the U.K., Unwin Hyman's books include trade, education
and academic topics.
</TEXT>
