<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE U.S. WON assurances from six nations and the EC that
they will agree to cut farm subsidies. But some Europeans at
the economic summit claimed victory because the understanding
doesn't call for the elimination of export subsidies, and
U.S. aides said tough talks lie ahead. Meanwhile, the summit
leaders agreed to follow different paths on the environment
and aid to the Soviets.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   U.S. banks were ordered to write off 20% of their $11.1
billion in loans to Brazil and an additional 20% of their
$2.9 billion in Argentine portfolios. The action could force
some banks, especially Citicorp, to boost reserves.
   ---
   Stock prices rose sharply on positive second-quarter
earnings and on bullish news for oil companies. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average jumped 41.83 points to 2932.67. The dollar
gained and bonds were flat.
   ---
   Wall Street bond dealers deluged the Treasury with what
amounted to bogus bids for seven-year notes to retaliate for
a change in auction rules.
   ---
   Five oil ministers from the Persian Gulf urged OPEC to
freeze its output ceiling to try to raise its average crude
price to at least $18 a barrel. Oil prices gained on the
news, as did the shares of U.S. oil companies.
   ---
   A grand jury indicted Edwin T. McBirney III, former owner
of defunct Sunbelt Savings, in the second big indictment by
U.S. thrift-fraud prosecutors in the past month.
   ---
   Five senators violated ethics rules in the S&amp;L scandal, a
citizens group argued. Meanwhile, Bush voiced confidence in
the integrity of his son, who faces a thrift-related probe.
   ---
   PS New Mexico was approached by a small venture-capital
firm about acquiring the utility. The move may flush out
other interested buyers. PS New Mexico's stock rose $2 to
$11.75.
   ---
   The first factory for making computer chips with
superconducting materials is to be unveiled today by
Conductus, a tiny Silicon Valley firm.
   ---
   Banks would be required to adhere to securities
regulations if they market investment trusts to compete with
mutual funds, the SEC announced.
   ---
   First Executive is seeking to keep secret the full
contents of a consulting report that the insurer said proved
its financial strength and viability.
   ---
   CBS Inc. posted a 16% increase in second-quarter profit.
But the company said the prospect for continued growth this
year is "uncertain."
   ---
   The Chicago Merc will allow two traders convicted Monday
on federal felony charges to keep trading for their own
accounts pending a hearing.
   ---
   Most U.S. voters believe Bush is breaking his no-tax
pledge, but they don't much blame him for it and are resigned
to a tax increase, according to a Wall Street Journal/NBC
poll.
   ---
   Hartmarx halved its dividend and took a $51 million
after-tax charge. A sales slump has hurt the clothing firm.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 162,220,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2932.67, up 41.83; transportation 1155.29, up 9.67; utilities
204.79, up 1.19.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3410.30, off
0.73.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.36, up 0.70; spot
index 132.46, up 0.35.
   Dollar: 148.50 yen, up 0.20; 1.6560 marks, up 0.0135.
</TEXT>
