<HL>
   Big Board Specialists'
   Return on Capital
   Drops to Rate of 4.4%
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Returns on capital for the 46 specialist firms
at the New York Stock Exchange in the first quarter dropped
to a 4.4% annual rate after taxes, the Big Board said.
   Specialists are firms that use their own capital to ensure
an orderly market in certain assigned stocks for which they
are responsible. Their job is to facilitate speedy trading,
stepping in to buy shares when too many sell orders pile up
and selling some when investors rush to buy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First-quarter returns were down from an 8.6% annualized
rate in the first quarter of 1989, but better than the
negative 1.7% return posted for the fourth quarter.
   The exchange said specialists' profits amounted to $9
million after taxes in the first quarter, down 57% from $21
million in the year-earlier period.
   Meanwhile, the Big Board confirmed industry projections
that its 342 member brokerage firms that deal with the public
had a $486 million pretax loss in the first quarter, compared
with a $200 million pretax profit a year earlier. The loss
reflects $459 million in one-time retrenchment expenses at
certain member broker-dealers, including Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   The exchange said about 59% of the 342 firms reporting for
the quarter were profitable.
   Member brokerage firms' expenses for the quarter rose 2.5%
to $14 billion, their fourth-highest level ever. Revenue fell
2.5% to $13.52 billion, their seventh-highest level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900712-0016
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900712-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Safeway Inc.:
   Supermarket Firm Says Net
   Rose Threefold in Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
07/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   SWY
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Safeway Inc., citing improved gross and operating profit,
said net income rose threefold in the second quarter ended
June 16.
   Net rose to $23.6 million, or 25 cents a share, from $7.7
million, or 10 cents a year ago. Sales increased 5% to $3.44
billion from $3.27 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Oakland, Calif.-based company, which owns a chain of
supermarkets, said its operating profit margin was 3.85% of
sales, compared with 3.24% a year earlier, while interest
expenses declined. Gains in operating profit came from
improved buying, inventory control and mix of products, said
Safeway Vice President David Domeier. "Our ability to buy
better has a big impact on the bottom line," he said,
although he noted the net is a small percentage of sales.
   Safeway's stock closed at $16.625, up 50 cents, in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday.
</TEXT>
